comments.text: I can only speak for myself but I believe the approach that mounts a device in the collet is much more useful and accurate.  So, instead of saying 'take it down' I would suggest a couple different modifications or alternatives to your device.  First, try printing a 1/4" vertical column on your piece and try it in the collet.  It may work fine if you use sufficient infill.  A second approach would be to use a 1/4" bolt thru the horizontal piece in lieu of the 1/4" printed column.  Once the 1/4" part (either printed or bolt) is snugged up in the collet it will replicate the angle accurately as you rotate the device.
comments.author: atwooddon

comments.text: Neat idea --- Except    The collet nut is not what needs to be measured.  The collet is the critical piece to be perpendicular to the bed.  Just replace the outside six sided part with a vertical 1/4" piece and use that in the collet to check for perpendicular relative to the bed.

If you think this would be that far off from the collet I will take it down. You can slap this on at any angle and give it a spin and always get the same result I feel if you can get a 200mm circle fairly perpendicular all the way around the collet really should not be that far off from the nut, right?

comments.author: atwooddon

comments.text: While I think your idea is 'good' my concern is that you are measuring from a component that is not necessarily the same 'angle' as the bit will end up when mounted in the collet.  Please don't take my comment as a personal attack.  The smaller the bit diameter, the less you will see mill tracks in your horizontal machined parts. But even with a 1/16" end mill that is not perfectly perpendicular to the CNC bed, you will see tracks where one side of the bottom of the bit is closer to the bed than the other.  It only takes a fraction of a degree to see this defect.  So, as a coarse adjustment, your device should work well.  For finer/accurate adjustments, you need to mount the device in the collet.

title: Radio Shack Dune Warrior Wheel Shock/Strut Top

description.text:
One daughter played bumper cars with my other daughter and the spring shock departed into the yard somewhere. Unlike "hobby grade" RC cars, you apparently can't get replacement parts for these "branded" models. So, off to tinkercad and the 3d printer I went. Worked well, and scavenged a spring from an old pair of garden snips and back in the race! If you want a perfectly printed top, print it separate and glue it on the column, I printed it in one piece as appearance didn't matter, only function. This works with this model of Radio Shack RC car, maybe others.

Best part of this is that my daughter is now finally interested in this "3d Printer and design" stuff... ;-)

comments.text:
Hi,
I'm investigating some details about sax reed and mouthpiece.
Not clear what is the target you pursue?
In the instrument that uses reed and mouthpiece the resonance frequency of the reed shall be close to resonance frequency of the instrument at particular note, otherwise the instrument sounds quiet. Player changes point where his lips press on the reed and even put the mouthpiece inside the mouth (to reasonable depth) for higher frequencies resonance. What player is going to do with his lips having 4 reeds at 4 sides? Two reeds at opposite sides have some sense. Shall multiple reeds have different resonance, while the instrument have exactly one - current tone at a time? It may have some sence if e.g. one reed covers best low frequency resonance, while another covers best high frequencies resonance. But will sound be pleasant if two reeds with different own resonance will add to the sound simultaneously? This may be some target of investigation.

description.text:
You know those stupid little ultrasonic fog maker things that you always see? Awesome right? Well, except for a few problems, they always need 24v and never come with a power supply, and they spray water all over the place, and you can never find a container big enough to contain the spray. Well, here is my solution, a cute little box that should block spray from escaping, but allow the fog/mist to flow freely.
The mister sits in the bottom part which gets filled with water, the cord goes through the little hole in the side and the rubber stopper should fit snugly in the hole, the top part sits on top. When plugged in, the spray is blocked by the flaps that hang down from the top, but the fog can flow around the flaps and out through the openings on the other side. The outer edge of the bottom part is raised, where the inner edge of the top is raised, allowing the two parts to fit nicely together, and preventing and water dripping down the sides from exiting the container. A pretty neat solution I think, plus it looks cute, like some kind of ancient artefact maybe.
You will have to find your own 24v power supply though, can't print those (yet).

There are two version, the first version is smaller, it works, but doesn't allow very much fog to get out. Second version is bigger and has bigger openings, and should allow much more fog to escape, it should also accommodate slightly larger foggers.

I designed this case in order to make my 18650 2s packs neat and safe, but also as small and light as possible.
Here's a few simple pack assembly instructions, I will try and update this with some photos once I've had a chance to assemble another one.

Pack assembly instructions:
Step 1:
Take your two 18650 cells and solder a 20mm length of wire between the negative (-) and positive (+) terminals at one end of the cells. Be careful to make sure that the wire is well insulated on the positive end as only the centre of the pack is positive. If the wire is allowed to make contact between the centre terminal and the outside of the cell you will have a fire on your hands.
Step 2:
Attach a smaller wire to either end of the joiner piece and run it up the middle of the cells and leave it loose at the other end. This will be used for your the middle lead of balance connector.
Step 3:
Slide the two cells into the main part of the case and apply a drop of glue if required (most brands should be a snug fit).
Step 4:
Connect up the two remaining exposed terminals to the main power connector for your goggles/equipment paying careful attention to polarity.
Step 5:
Hook up an additional wire to each of the main terminals and connect them to your balance connector as shown in the picture above.
Step 6:
Ensure all connections are well insulated, route wires through the hole in the lid and then glue the lid in place.

Needless to say, I hold no responsibility for any injuries or damage you cause whilst trying to assemble this battery so do so at YOUR OWN RISK. If you don't feel comfortable working on bare cells, or are unsure of your abilities/my instructions find someone else to help you.

title: RotaVac - A Rotary Vacuum Pump
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
RotaVac is an experimental "centrifugal compressor", designed to be printable as a single piece and spun in a drill or machine to generate a negative pressure gradient.
RotaVac is designed to fit a standard 608 bearing like the sort used in Makerbots, so that a small nozzle (printed separately?) can be fitted through the bearing interior.
This is a pure experiment, and I'll post more when I have a chance to test it!

1.) Print with plenty of infill to make airtight. Print from SD recommended - Plenty of curves in this piece!
2.) Poke Bearing in the bottom
3.) Poke some kind of nozzle through the bearing
4.) Spin it counterclockwise (D'oh!) on a drill and use the negative pressure to create a negative-pressure container.
5.) Aspirate stuff into the container. Aspirating stuff directly into RotaVac (assuming it works at all) is not recommended, as it'll just fling it everywhere and make a big mess.

comments.text: How about spinning it in the opposite direction. That should force air out the nozzle creating a vacuum around the device. Put it all in a large tube with a narrow opening at the top and see how that works.
comments.author: jpcw

comments.text: We built this part at http://hacklab.tohacklab.to, hoping to be able to achieve a little vacuum power. It printed great, looks super cool. We tried rotating it at low speed using a drill, but didn't feel anything. We then removed the gear box from a standard DC motor, to get a 9000 RPM motor. Hooked up to this device, the device spins awesome, vibrating a lot if things are not perfectly centered. We used some bamboo fitted inside a bearing, inserted in the center hole. Holding the bamboo provides stability during operation (that's why bamboo is superior to plastic tubing!) But no pressure/suction is obvious. We did a smoke test using solder, and showed that there is a tiny amount of suction into the bamboo - the smoke is sucked in from up to about an inch away. My estimate of the suction power is about 0.1 PSI.

I think it pays for the time to have a look and, why not, contribute :) Anyway, I decided to share with you one tool I developed to support the figurine making process.
Basically, the part of the process we are talking about, consists of 3D parametric modelling (something like the attached examples), followed by sculpting (i.e. artistic modelling), and then all the 3D printing stuff (and, of course, finishing and painting!) Now, let's move to instructions!

To start playing, after downloading the files, you open the main_head OpenSCAD script and just press F5 to check that all is working fine, which means to compile the parametric head whose parameters are defined within the script - being my head :) You should obtain something like in head-step.15.png. To accommodate with the process, change the step parameter value from 0 to 15 and see how things evolve. You have some snapshots to compare with :) In early steps, try to change some head parameter values. Please note that the stuff is generated top-down, and so is the code written ;) Once you got the point, you're ready for creation! Just to avoid messing things up, create a new folder and copy the 2 .scad files in there. Take 2 pictures of your preferred head, say yours, one from the front and one from the side, open them in your 2D graphical app (I would recommend Inkscape) and generate 2 contour files, called face.dxf and side.dxf respectively, saving them in your new folder. Then, simply open main_head.scad and start do the job and have fun. Now with all new knowledge, you may reconsider contributing to Figure The Moments campaign :) Give it a try!

description.text:
Out with the old reel, and in with a new one! Some problems that come with printing parts using the last bit of plastic in a reel have been bugging me for a while, as it's usually difficult to judge whether something that you want to print will use up all the remaining plastic, and how it does so. You can take an approach of printing something so large that there isn't quite enough plastic to complete it, and the object gets truncated, but there are very few basic printer parts with a large unnecessary section at the top for your uncertainty to fall within, so most of the time one can't be sure if the printer will run out of plastic before finishing a crucial section.
You could also run a few print jobs of very small parts, but then you either have a significant length of waste plastic at the end, a final print of small parts that may not be useable if you run out halfway through, or you end up printing one of Zeno's paradoxes to try and avoid either of those fates. I've tried to develop something that solves the first option, while always producing something useful at the end, so long as you're within a very wide printing margin. I'd say this print comes with an element of a nice surprise in terms of what size your box is, but you might want to check on the print as it runs out of filament, and stop it on a layer just before the loose end goes past the filament drive, so that you don't end up with a mess or have the extruder drive grinding away at its idler for a while. Alternatively, if you have some awesome ninja printing skills, you might be able to get a new reel of plastic on whatever spool you use, in time to feed the new starting loose end in directly behind the old end without stopping the print. However, if you could manage that without hiccups in nozzle output, then you wouldn't even need this thing to begin with. These handy trays can be used to sort small fasteners, jewellery, fishing tackle (all the same really) or similar bits, with a lid that gets completed at the start of the print.

Pick a box to suit your printbed and whatever you want to store in it, edit one of the STEP files in a CAD program to suit your needs, or even make something similar yourself. The versions I rendered already should fit without trouble on a Prusa or Makerbot buildspace respectively; they all have 2mm walls throughout, with a 2.5mm lid and base. The largest and most-walled version, which I tested (see photo), should use about 24.5m of 2.8mm filament if printed all the way to the top using a 0.5mm nozzle, 2-layer walls and 20% line infill, according to the estimation in pronterface.
With the amount of plastic I had remaining on a spool (see photo), I produced the tray shown. It measures about 27mm tall of the possible total 95mm (plus lid). Since I used ABS the bottom corners of the tray were warped upwards quite a bit for a short distance into the box, even though I use quite a reasonably high-powered heated printbed, so the print could be a little bit tricky in that respect.

This extension consists of 3 parts:

  • a bracket to hold the LCD into the casing, with the ability to attach the LCD circuitboard with 4 screws to this attachement. (glue it in place with a few drops of superglue)
  • a bracket to hold the RPI. (RPI 3 in my case), also put in place with a few drops of superglue.

The strip with the mounting holes, fits underneath the baseplate (just drill 3 holes), and is the samen height as the feet for the cyclone I designed earlier

This magnetic keychain connector keeps your house keys and car keys together in your pocket or purse but allows easy separation when needed. It uses readily available 1/4â X 1/16â Neodymium Disc Magnets embedded in the ABS during the printing process. There are two versions included; one using a single magnet and another using two magnets. The single magnet version is a bit more compact and serves a double function of serving to hold a supply of extra magnets to have with you at all times (Iâm constantly finding uses for these babies). The double version has a stronger magnetic field and works better if you donât need to carry extra magnets. In either case, simply slice and print the corresponding stl, pausing after the pocket is formed, just before the enclosing layer. I use use the @pause feature within Repetier-Host which works beautifully. Insert the magnet(s) and resume printing. Works fine at .3mm resolution. This project was designed in FreeCAD. Iâve included the FreeCAD fcstd files in case you want to make modifications. One source for the magnets is:
http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B001ANVAHI/ Enjoy!

This project requires printing to the top of the pocket, pausing, adding the magnet(s), and resuming the print. I found Repetier-Host to be the most intuitive for accomplishing this so these instructions are written for that tool. If you know how to do the same thing using Pronterface or another program, please add instructions in the comments.
  • Load two (or more) of the stlâs into Repetier-Host
  • Slice the stl (I use Slic3r). These are small objects but .3mm still works fine.
  • Using the Visualization tab in the G-Code editor while watching the 3D View pane, choose Single Layer and cycle through the layers until you find the topmost open layer. (At .3mm, this will probably be somewhere around layer 8 for the single version and layer 14 for the double)
  • Insert a line of code into the G-Code between when the open layer ends and the closed layer begins.
  • Type this code into that line: @pause Add Magnet(s)
  • Run the job
  • When the pause dialog pops up, insert magnet(s) into each pocket. Be sure to observe polarity of each magnet so the segments attract each other instead of repel.
  • Continue the print job.
  • Done!

This thing is handy if you want to roll your own icom microphone.
Held held icoms are popular in sports aviation for both airband VHF and UHF.
They often are hooked to helmets or headsets.
Icom, baofeng, kenwood and other radios use a very similar looking plug but they are not compatible electrically. Icom is the odd one out. Plugs and accessories for baofengs are common and cheap but don't work with icom. The cheap plugs do not bring out all the signals and are un-shielded. If you make your own using my thing and some stereo plugs you can access all the signals.
There is a choice in shells - with or without cable hole or anchor for a zip-tie.
This is still in progress so more info may follow.

Update - my ic-41W has arrived and it is different to the ic-a15 - new things uploaded.

I sing at a church that keeps the lights pretty low for a part of the service.  We (singers and musicians) have a hard time seeing the sheet music and words on our music stands.  We tried book lights and so on but they just don't cut it very well, so i decided to make my own.  it runs off 2 9v batteries wired in series with a small toggle and a 3 pod LED light.  The base/cover piece doesn't work the best as the tab that clip in are weak by design unless it it printed on its side but i will work on that when i have time.  Right now the base is just friction fitted in and it stays fine.  Feel free to comment or make suggestions or change it as you need to.  I just ask if you base off my design you just link back to mine to we can all see the evolution.

I printed on a Solidoodle 3 at .2 layers with 50% infill. Bed temp at 115 head temp at 200. Nothing really difficult about this print at all. I didnt put the holes in the print file because it all depends on where you want the switch and how your lights wiring is also. You want as small of a switch as possible because there is just barely enough room for wires and switch once the batteries are in there. You will need:
2 9v batteries
2 9v battery connectors
1 LED light (your choice of size i used a 3 pod)
1 micro toggle switch

title: Flexible walnut nutcracker
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This nutcracker is designed to highlight the strength characteristics of Innofil3D filament for their recent contest. The nutcracker is printed in their recycled PET and is subjected to a lot of flex, tension and pressure at the same time. And still, it can crack walnuts with ease! It is designed to fit the average walnut, but other same-sized nuts should work as well.

Video:https://youtu.be/dnCkOjlhwtY

Please note: you will need the right filament with the right amount of flex as well as strength. I have tested mine for days and it is still going strong, but I don't have any long term use experience (yet). It may break after flexing it excessively and fatiguing the plastic. This should be seen more as a proof of concept to impress your friends than an everyday household item ;)

description.text:
It's a quadruped robot that using 8x 9G servos with ultrasonic sensor. You may use your own controller board. In this case I am using regular Arduino with expansion shield and a 7.2V lipo battery with 5V UBEC to regulate the voltage down. VIDEO:
http://youtu.be/fWp43eDwpkA Things you need:
9g micro servo x8
1 1/4" M2 or M3 bolts x12
Nylon nuts for bolts x12 (Other nuts works too but Nylon is better)
10"~12" Aluminum tubing (OD5/32 and OD3/16 for each) Tools I use:
Electronic driller*(Sometimes the hole is too small)
Tube cutter
pliers(for bolt I used)
allen keys(for bolt I used)
File (Smooth out the surface on parts)
AB cold welder (To glue the bolt inside of servo bracket which connect to body as shown in picture. The one with white bracket) You may want to try this FREDUINO board alone without any servo shields or regulator since it provides 2A output on board. I tried to plug 8 9G servos on it and it works fine with my chassis. Nicely designed!
http://www.elecfreaks.com/wiki/index.php?title=Freaduino_UNO 2014.11.30 UPDATE:
I have expand the main servo brackets(Left and Right) slightly larger(about 1 mm) for some larger servos. you may find them in name: bracket2_L_ext.stl & bracket2_R_ext.stl.

You will need 3/16" OD aluminum tubing for spacing in between joints as shown in picture. Also some 1 1/4" bolts and nylan nuts to lock parts in place. (In some case you might need to file out some holes from printed parts depands on the bolts you use.) Metal tubing is to reduce the friction in joints, the most important is to having these tubing sticking out a bit so when you screw down the bolts and nuts won't contact surface on parts that cause friction. It just suggestion that I use, you might got some better idea to do this. Drop me a line so others can learn from your idea. For Ultrasonic sensor housing: I made it for SR-04. Others might not fit in this case or some other from different places might need to file the housing to fit in. I just use 3M double sided type to attache it on the top body plate. They works quiet well and firmed. As for body plates I got 2 versions. Pick whatever you like. Notice the file "bracket2_connx" is I made to connect top and bottome plates. You don't have to use it. Actually these plate are easy to made. I strongly recommand you make your own to show more personality ;) UPDATE:2013, Oct 8
Ok! As some people have asked so I have upload my code @Github. https://github.com/hardmouse/TurtleBot_2DOF
I have warned, my code is very very bad. So bad that I don't even think it's a good idea for starter. It might lead you to wrong direction for programming. So, before you check the code; please think twice.....or more than 3 times.

description.text:
A magazine for 7 to 8 NERF-Darts. Compatible with N-Strike Elite (tested with unmodified Rampage and Stryfe). Additinal parts:
  • 2x M3 nut and bolt
  • zig-zag spring (has to be custom made)

Print out all three parts. It should be fairly obvious how these fit together. You will also need two M3 screws and nuts and a spring.  
Making a good spring is actually the hardest part of this build. I used spring-steel wire and bent it into a zig-zag shape with the help of a piece of wood with some nails. Use an original magazine for inspirantion.
